# explain git comands, diffrents between git clone, git fork? what i need to know before starting to work with git and othre peope and ai agnets

Git clone creates a local copy of a repository on your machine, keeping it linked to the remote for syncing changes via push and pull. Git fork, specific to platforms like GitHub, creates a full independent copy under your account on the server, ideal for contributing to projects without direct access.[^1_1][^1_2]

## Key Git Commands

Start with basics like `git init` to create a repo, `git add` to stage changes, and `git commit -m "message"` to save them locally. Use `git status` often to check your working directory, `git log --oneline` for commit history, and `git branch` to manage branches. For remotes, `git remote -v` lists connections, `git fetch` updates info without merging, and `git pull` fetches and merges.[^1_3][^1_4]

## Clone vs Fork Differences

| Aspect | Git Clone | Git Fork |
| :-- | :-- | :-- |
| Location | Local machine copy | Server-side copy on your GitHub account [^1_1][^1_2] |
| Ownership | No new ownership; linked to original [^1_5] | Full control over your copy [^1_1] |
| Syncing | Direct push/pull if permitted [^1_1] | Use pull requests to contribute back [^1_6] |
| Use Case | Daily work on shared repo [^1_7] | Open-source contributions [^1_2] |

Fork first, then clone your fork for local work.[^1_1]

## Prep for Team and AI Collaboration

Install Git and configure `git config --global user.name` and `user.email` for identity. Learn branching: create feature branches with `git checkout -b feature/name`, work there, and merge via pull requests (PRs) to avoid main branch chaos. Always pull from main before starting (`git pull origin main`), commit small changes with descriptive messages, and resolve conflicts by editing files then committing.[^1_4][^1_8][^1_9][^1_10][^1_11]

For teams, follow a workflow: clone shared repo, branch per task, push branches, open PRs for review. With AI agents, use separate branches or Git worktrees (`git worktree add ../agent-task branch-name`) so agents work isolated, then review and merge their PRs manually. Avoid force pushes on shared branches and sync daily to minimize conflicts.[^1_12][^1_8][^1_13][^1_14][^1_11]
